Explanations on Global Competitiveness
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Center for International Development at Harvard University published the Global Competitiveness Report for 2001.
In the study covering 75 countries, Finland, the United States, and Canada take the top three positions, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe form the bottom three.
(All rankings can be found at www.weforum.com.)
As a co-responsible leader of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Is there also an economic competition among the countries besides the military one?
Does it even make sense to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is defined very precisely: namely, as the ability of a country to achieve sustainable economic growth over the medium term, that is, within a period of five years.
This definition does not, however, mean that the competitiveness of one country simultaneously says something about the lack of competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries on Earth could achieve higher growth at the same time.
Nevertheless, it is sensible to create a ranking of countries in terms of their growth potential.
Every country is interested in finding out whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep up with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In many respects, economic growth can be compared to a sporting competition, where the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
Countries compete, for example, for internationally mobile capital.
The more a country can gain from foreign direct investments, the less another country will gain.
This becomes completely clear when countries compete for a specific investment project.
When Intel plans a new semiconductor plant, various countries are invited to submit proposals.
The competition for the contract is fierce, and often bids are made with tax incentives, infrastructure improvements, and even adjustments to study programs at the local technical university.
This year, we assessed the competitiveness (growth potential) of a country based on three broad criteria: (1) Technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we determined indicators whose average values were calculated using a specific method in order to then create an overall growth and competition index.
The criterion of technology refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and to adopt technologies developed elsewhere.
Some countries, such as the USA, Japan, Korea, Israel, and Sweden, invest heavily in research and development and thus achieve high levels of innovation.
Other countries such as Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and therefore achieve little in terms of new products and processes.
Innovative countries also enjoy a high level of prosperity due to these innovations.
In this area, the USA, Canada, and Finland occupy the top three positions on the ranking list.
The criterion "public institutions" refers to the quality of administration.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts incorruptible and impartial?
Can we trust that the government will fulfill its obligations properly?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and corrupt judges.
High ethical standards promote economic performance.
In this regard, the Nordic countries are world leaders, and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also at the top of the ranking.
Corruption is almost unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced state budget, a realistic exchange rate for the national currency, the ability of businesses and the government to obtain loans on the capital market, and high confidence that the government will fulfill its financial obligations.
Taking the example of Asia in the late 1990s, we learned that a macroeconomic crisis can destroy economic growth, even if companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries in terms of macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we noticed that the world economy can be divided into two categories of countries: the innovation-friendly and the non-innovation-friendly.
Only about 20 countries are actively engaged in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the richest in the world, a remarkable system of technological innovations is considered a prerequisite for continuous competitiveness.
Universities must be excellent, state laboratories should reach world-class standards, and the government and industry should strongly invest in research and development.
A key factor for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who, after completing compulsory education, attend higher schools and universities.
In the United States and Canada, this proportion is 80%.
For the "non-innovation-friendly" countries, technology is just as important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed within the country itself.
Some countries specialize in importing new technologies, while others do less.
A significant portion of technology imports occurred over the past ten or fifteen years within the framework of foreign direct investments.
American companies that heavily invested in Mexico or Taiwanese companies that invested in Mainland China also brought new technologies that increased the efficiency of production in the respective economy of the target country.
Therefore, it was entirely sensible for the concerned countries to make every effort to secure these overseas investments: they bring not only capital, but also new technologies.
A strength and at the same time a weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is medium-term oriented and does not focus on the next one to two years.
Our rankings are not suitable for assessing short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of the major economies.
It is therefore ironic that many of the countries that are ranked first this year, such as the USA or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while others that are ranked further down, such as China (ranked 39th), are not affected by the global recession.
In part, the slowdown in the economy is linked to the terrorist attacks of September 11, but it is also increasingly clear that the American economy and other economies connected to it through trade and production networks were already sliding into recession before September.
Nevertheless, we believe that this is a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the United States will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth in the next five years.
